          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed"><strong>Then the opposite:</strong> A fitness instructor who genuinely needed 7 apps. Booking, payments, video hosting, nutrition tracking, member area, email marketing, analytics. Wix handled everything seamlessly. Zyro couldn't - she would've needed multiple tools patched together.</p>
          <div class="bg-rose-100 border-l-[4px] border-rose-500 p-4 my-4">
            <p class="text-sm text-rose-900 font-medium"><strong>The truth:</strong> Zyro for simple sites where you want to avoid feature bloat. Wix when you genuinely need complex functionality. Most people overestimate their needs.</p>
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">I've switched dozens of clients from Wix to Zyro. They never missed the features. They loved the lower bills. Be honest about what you actually need.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Use Cases -->
    <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-6 mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">Choose Based on Your Priorities</h2>
      <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
        <li><strong>Choose Wix (8.2/10) if:</strong> You want extensive features, you need app integrations, budget allows $17+/mo, you value flexibility.</li>
        <li><strong>Choose Zyro (7.5/10) if:</strong> Budget is $9-15/mo, you want AI content help, you need a simple site, ease matters.</li>
        <li><strong>Wix is better for:</strong> Complex sites, e-commerce, membership sites, advanced features, app integrations.</li>
        <li><strong>Zyro is better for:</strong> Personal sites, simple business, budget projects, beginners, AI content assistance.</li>
